          "title": "Theophanic judgment — earthquake, sword, plague, fire, and brimstone",
          "body": "Verses 18-22 are among the most concentrated accumulations of divine-judgment imagery in the Hebrew prophets. Six instruments are deployed simultaneously: a great earthquake that shakes the entire created order (38:19-20), sword called against Gog on all God's mountains (38:21), internecine panic causing every man's sword to turn against his brother (38:21), pestilence (38:22), blood (38:22), torrential flooding rain (38:22), hailstones (38:22), fire, and brimstone (38:22). The combination is deliberate and allusive: the hail, fire, and brimstone echo Sodom's destruction (Genesis 19:24) and the Exodus plagues (Exodus 9:22-24); the earthquake evokes Sinai theophany (Exodus 19:18; Psalm 68:8); the internecine panic recalls Gideon's battle (Judges 7:22) and Jehoshaphat's victory (2 Chronicles 20:23). God is not using novel instruments — He is deploying the full arsenal of His historical self-disclosure in one concentrated eschatological moment. The judgment is not merely destructive; it is revelatory. The nations are not simply destroyed; they are confronted with the God who destroyed them."
